      "beat_count": 8,
      "conditioning_notes": "Both `<CHAR_A>` and `<CHAR_B>` share the 🪺 Nest core — their love of caring and fear of not being needed creates a low-key standoff at the top of the arc: two people who exist to help cannot help each other because neither will admit to needing it. The collision over `<CHAR_C>`'s spilled bag is where that dynamic erupts — two Nests descending on the same problem, going left simultaneously, unable to yield. The named granola bars are the crack in the wall: a detail that reveals how far each Nest has extended their care into the anonymous world. `<CHAR_C>`'s ⚓ Anchor core — fearing being overlooked — drives the disruption and the naming of what's happening. The Anchor is the one who sees the pattern and says it out loud, which is what finally lets the two Nests stop competing and start recognizing each other. The threshold location is never described — it lives in the suspended state, the halted traffic, the sense that characters are about to become something they weren't before. The tension falls across the arc not through resolution of a plot obstacle but through two strangers discovering they are the same kind of person."
